<paragraph pageId="349" pageNumber="350">
Subgenus 
<taxonomicName LSID="D1B2E622-29A4-502D-961C-7ED87E365739" authority="Casey, 1918" authorityName="Casey" authorityYear="1918" class="Hexapoda" family="Carabidae" genus="Bembidion" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="(Hydriomicrus)" order="Coleoptera" pageId="349" pageNumber="350" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subGenus" subGenus="Hydriomicrus">Hydriomicrus Casey, 1918</taxonomicName>
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="349" pageNumber="350" type="reference_group">
<paragraph pageId="349" pageNumber="350">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Casey" authorityYear="1918" class="Insecta" family="Carabidae" genus="Hydriomicrus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Coleoptera" pageId="349" pageNumber="350" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Hydriomicrus</taxonomicName>
Casey, 1918: 87. Type species: 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Haldeman" authorityYear="1843" class="Insecta" family="Carabidae" genus="Leja" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Coleoptera" pageId="349" pageNumber="350" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="semistriata">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="349" pageNumber="350">Leja semistriata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Haldeman, 1843 designated by Lindroth (1963b: 305). Etymology. From the Greek 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="349" pageNumber="350">hydrias</emphasis>
(from water) and 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="349" pageNumber="350">micros</emphasis>
(small, little), possibly alluding to the small size of the adult and the habitat requirement of the species [masculine].
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="350" pageNumber="351" type="diversity">
<paragraph pageId="350" pageNumber="351">
<pageBreakToken pageId="350" pageNumber="351" start="start">Diversity</pageBreakToken>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="350" pageNumber="351">Five North American species, two in the east and three in the west.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="350" pageNumber="351" type="identification">
<paragraph pageId="350" pageNumber="351">Identification.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="350" pageNumber="351">
<normalizedToken originalValue="Lindrothâ€™s">Lindroth's</normalizedToken>
(1963b: 212-229) key to 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Latreille" authorityYear="1802" class="Hexapoda" family="Carabidae" genus="Bembidion" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Coleoptera" pageId="350" pageNumber="351" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="350" pageNumber="351">Bembidion</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
included all but one species (
<taxonomicName authorityName="Casey" authorityYear="1918" class="Hexapoda" family="Carabidae" genus="Bembidion" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Coleoptera" pageId="350" pageNumber="351" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="innocuum">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="350" pageNumber="351">Bembidion innocuum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
); the two species found in Canada were treated in detail (Lindroth 1963b: 306).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
